<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-727-004  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 727 004.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Sept 14 1989 n1181 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Simplify the work but don't remove the choice. (fourth-generationlanguages)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rogers, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The software industry needs to adopt fourth generation programminglanguages to keep up with hardware developments.andP;  Inherentweaknesses in current products are hindering the progress of thefourth generation market.andP;  Many products provide easy solutions to80 percent of the programming, but no solution to the remaining 20percent with complex programming problems.andP;  The accepted solutionis to interface to a third generation language, like C, for thecomplex pieces of a program.andP;  This defeats the benefits of using afourth generation language in the first place.andP;  Speed of executionand memory consumption are additional problems with fourthgeneration languages.andP;  A programming environment is needed thathas powerful fourth generation language commands that areequivalent to procedural or third generation commands.andP;  This wouldensure that any program written in C or Cobol can also be writtenfaster in the fourth generation language.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Programming LanguagesFourth-Generation LanguagesProduct DevelopmentCode GenerationSoftware PublishersMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>